<subSubSection id="D74E28DB7DCC372EB37BC091395FDB44" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="102EBDE5046E8838C06BB2855C89350A" pageNumber="409">
Etymology Gr 
<taxonomicName id="E00C44E8A0FD1A19D93554BB4569EDE4" LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:181865" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole drepanon Wilson" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole drepanon Wilson" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="409" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="drepanon">drepanon</taxonomicName>
, sickle, alluding to the propodeal spines.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="E942F2C5959AC76C03EA2A230075603C" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="7341B31323CAEE59DBC8C98D5F4AD4A1" pageNumber="409">
DIAGNOSIS Similar to the Dominican endemic 
<taxonomicName id="5BCF8C6F8919F65455BB7C067AA490C9" LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:181881" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole harlequina Wilson" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole harlequina Wilson" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="409" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="harlequina">harlequina</taxonomicName>
, differing from it and all other 
<taxonomicName id="150BE92290AF1C96E6226814E5D9DDAC" LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:24885" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole Westwood" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole Westwood" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="409" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Pheidole</taxonomicName>
as follows. Major: propodeal spines very thick, curved, sickle-shaped, and much longer than the propodeal basal face anterior to them; head and body bicolored as depicted; all of dorsal surface of head except for occipital margin carinulate and weakly rugulose; head slightly broader than long; petiolar peduncle very long; postpetiole from above diamond-shaped.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="6933A53502F17825E0D94ADCFCE215CA" type="description">
<paragraph id="FD2F02E57C2366912C820028F5D80C95" pageNumber="409">Minor: propodeal spines very thick, curved, and sickle-shaped, much longer than the propodeal basal face anterior to them; body concolorous medium brown.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="CADFE6807316D24CA21B5A519F045FFA" pageNumber="409">Measurements (mm) Holotype major: HW 1.04, HL 1.02, SL 0.70, EL 0.14, PW 0.50. Paratype minor: HW 0.48, HL 0.52, SL 0.64, EL 0.08, PW 0.32.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="0C2BFA9B78C903A6B1CC0B10F26A8512" pageNumber="409">Color Major: body medium brown except for the front of the head (as depicted), as well as dorsum of promesonotum and anterior half of first gastral tergite, which are brownish yellow.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="4FDF9DBAFA23ED7426059E2FE7D9A0F9" pageNumber="409">Minor: body concolorous medium brown, appendages light to yellowish brown.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="B143BA510CA026501DD7C7222E847EBF" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="6B77EA2E0F0BFF8797998281B71A338E" pageNumber="409">
Range 
<taxonomicName id="4199864527396AA624C6CC66376141DF" LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:181865" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole drepanon Wilson" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole drepanon Wilson" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="409" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="drepanon">P. drepanon</taxonomicName>
is evidently an endemic of the Dominican Republic; a second collection was made by P. S. Ward 22 km north of Pedemales, 18AÃ‚Â°09TN* 71AÃ‚Â°35'W, 1600 m. 
<taxonomicName id="74AB83E5E5C89EAEA02CECB4105D4CE9" LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:181865" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole drepanon Wilson" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole drepanon Wilson" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="409" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="drepanon">P. drepanon</taxonomicName>
might also occur in Haiti, especially since the type locality is close to the border.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="403D404898E5ADE4FF549A383FF0AD20" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph id="16D99B90170F7D54983475BB470776E5" pageNumber="409">Biology The type colony was collected in tropical evergreen forest.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
